title: The Best There Ever Was
body:
so I know people have head canons, and extrapolate with pokemon games. But why not take everything at face value?

There’s this kid whose just moved in next to you, but they never eat or sleep and you rarely see them. They became the best trainer in your region in about a week. You ask their mom (what happened to their dad?). They only got their starter when they moved here, she says. You start looking closer at them. You find they’ve beaten an entire criminal organisation. You notice that they’re… efficient. Their pokemon are chosen for the situation. They act friendly with their pokemon but you can tell it’s just a way to increase their strength.

Oh. They’re in your room. You don’t have a problem with that. They walk up to you and stare into your eyes with a blank expression. Your eyes flicker to the badges pinned to their shirt. You don’t have any pokemon. You’re not a trainer. You give them a poke ball. Where did you get that? They walk out. You wonder what you were thinking before. There’s nothing wrong with the kid. They’re a strong trainer after all. The strongest trainer. They’ll always be. Why else would everyone challenge them?

summary: The official announcement of Sword & Shield has provided me with motivation to go back and play a bit more of Ultra Sun.  As it...
caption:
The official announcement of Sword & Shield has provided me with motivation to go back and play a bit more of Ultra Sun.  As it happens, I wasn’t very far from Hank, my shiny Shuppet, evolving into a shiny Banette.  Unfortunately, as with shuppet, Banette is one of those pokemon where the shiny palette doesn’t change very much from the regular palette, being a sort of navy blue instead of a charcoal grey.  Honestly, to the extent I can even tell them apart when I’m not looking directly at them, I actually kind of prefer the regular coloration.

That said, I don’t dislike shiny Banette at all.  Banette in general is just a pretty cool pokemon, what with the cursed doll motif, a cool/creepy zipper mouth, and a lot of personality.  Especially with its mega form, though sadly I can’t access that in USUM until the endgame, and the shiny colors don’t really hinder that.  The one significant complaint I have about Banette’s design, which applies equally to both the regular and the shiny colors, is that the zipper ‘teeth’ don’t come apart as they should when it opens its mouth, instead all the gold teeth stay together on one side.  Hopefully in future generations they’ll fix that.

title: Series that defined my childhood
body:
I recently made a post about how Pokemon was my childhood. That much is true, but it wasn’t the only series that filled that niche. The other ones were Star Wars and Yu-Gi-Oh. 

True, I’m too young to be of the generation that grew up with the original trilogy, but I did get to grow up with the prequels. Say what you will about the prequel trilogy, but I enjoyed the storytelling and characters and the stunning battles and visuals. True, there was Jar Jar Binks and bad dialogue, but nothing’s perfect, right? I kind of got to grow up with the original trilogy too because it was remastered some time in my childhood and re-released. I collected Star Wars LEGO sets as a kid and had a lot of fun playing Star Wars scenarios with them. I still like collecting Star Wars sets as an AFOL (adult fan of LEGO). Like Pokemon, Star Wars stuck with me. I never stopped being a fan. There’s some definitely nostalgia there. 

Then there’s Yu-Gi-Oh, a show about grown men playing an extremely dangerous children’s trading card game. I can’t say I’m much into Yu-Gi-Oh now, but back then, I was obsessed. I insisted on having my mom tape episodes on VHS (remember those?). I was also an avid card collector. 

Then there’s the proverbial elephant in the room. Harry Potter. It was a fad back then. I didn’t know bad media from good media as a kid, so of course I liked it. I also liked Jar Jar Binks back then. Go figure. But never would I say that it defined my childhood the way Star Wars, Yu-Gi-Oh and Pokemon did. For one thing, I wanted to be a Yu-Gi-Oh duelist as a kid, or a Pokemon trainer, or wanted to explore the Star Wars galaxy, but go to a school for wizards and wave around a stick of wood? No way. Currently, I couldn’t detest this piece of garbage series more. Heck, I’m pretty sure the tears of butthurt Harry Potter fans are one of the most important spices of life.
